:INFO
How to Warp a Rigid Heddle Loom Step by Step
Warping is the most technical part of setting up a rigid heddle loom. A methodical approach prevents tangled warp and tension problems before weaving begins.

:PATH
Calculate Your Warp Needs
Sett times width gives you ends; finished length plus waste gives you thread length.
|
:INFO
Calculate Your Warp Needs
Sett (ends per inch) x desired width = total warp ends needed. Finished length + 24 inches loom waste = length per warp thread. If you are weaving a 60-inch scarf at 8 inches wide with 8 EPI: 8 x 8 = 64 warp ends, each 84 inches long. Wind 64 threads at 84 inches each on a warping board.

:PATH
Wind the Warp with a Cross
Figure-eight the last two pegs at the start to create a cross.
|
:INFO
Wind the Warp with a Cross
The cross preserves thread order. At the start of your warp peg, wind: over peg 1, under peg 2, back over peg 2, under peg 1. This creates a figure-eight cross. Every subsequent wind follows the same path through these two pegs. The cross prevents threads from tangling during threading and shows which thread is next.

:PATH
Transfer and Thread the Heddle
Move the warp to the loom with lease sticks preserving the cross.
|
:INFO
Transfer and Thread the Heddle
Insert lease sticks through the cross before removing the warp from the warping board. Transfer to the loom with the cross near the front. Thread from right to left: take the first thread from the cross and thread it through a slot; take the next and thread it through the adjacent hole. Repeat across. Tie threads in groups of 8 to 10 to the front apron rod with a lark's head knot.

:NOTE
Beam Under Tension to Prevent Soft Spots
As you wind the warp onto the back beam, maintain firm, consistent tension. Place strips of cardboard or warp sticks between layers to prevent warp threads from embedding into earlier layers. Soft spots in the wound warp cause uneven tension during weaving and produce an uneven fell line.
